---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<Layout title="Towns That Already Won">
  <div class="content">
    <span class="card-tag" style="background: rgba(230, 57, 70, 0.2); color: #E63946;">Proof It Works</span>
    <h1>Arizona Towns Already Did This</h1>
    <p class="subtitle" style="color: var(--color-muted); font-size: 1.15rem;">
      Getting Flock cameras removed is not a fantasy and it is not a big-city thing. Five Arizona communities have already canceled or blocked their contracts. Same state, same network, same company. Here's how they did it.
    </p>

    <h2>Flagstaff</h2>
    <p>
      The clearest template. After roughly nine months of resident organizing, the Flagstaff City Council voted <strong>unanimously on December 16, 2025</strong> to cancel its Flock contract. All ~36 cameras were deactivated immediately, and Flock physically removed them by February 2026.
    </p>
    <p>
      The key lesson for Safford: the police department had already added guardrails, shorter retention, access limited to local agencies, a ban on immigration use. The council canceled anyway, deciding that lingering concern about the company and the network outweighed the benefits. One resident summed up the whole fight in a single line, answering the Flock CEO's claim that critics just want "chaos": <strong>"Is it chaos to want checks and balances?"</strong>
    </p>
    <p class="source">Sources: Arizona Daily Sun, KNAU, KJZZ, FOX10, GovTech, City of Flagstaff (Dec 2025&ndash;Feb 2026).</p>

    <h2>Sedona</h2>
    <p>
      Police had quietly installed 11 Flock cameras without notifying the city council. Once the council found out, they held a public meeting, heard residents, and moved to end the contract and remove the cameras. Sedona's action came first and helped trigger the Flagstaff fight next door.
    </p>
    <p class="source">Sources: Arizona Free Enterprise Club; KNAU; KJZZ (Sept&ndash;Dec 2025).</p>

    <h2>South Tucson</h2>
    <p>
      The South Tucson City Council voted <strong>5-1-1 to cancel</strong> its Flock contract, with members citing fears about the data being shared with ICE. The closest model to Safford in spirit: a small, working-class city that decided the immigration-surveillance risk wasn't worth it.
    </p>
    <p class="source">Sources: Tucson Spotlight; KGUN9 (Feb 2026).</p>

    <h2>Cochise County</h2>
    <p>
      A rural Arizona county that <strong>blocked Flock cameras</strong> rather than letting them in. Proof that the fight isn't only about removal after the fact, it's also about refusing the contract before the cameras go up.
    </p>
    <p class="source">Source: AZPM; regional reporting (2026).</p>

    <h2>Sierra Vista</h2>
    <p>
      Wound down its grant-funded Flock cameras rather than continuing the program. Another small Arizona city, another contract that didn't get renewed.
    </p>
    <p class="source">Source: regional Arizona reporting (2026).</p>

    <h2>What They Have in Common</h2>
    <div class="card">
      <ul class="card-specifics">
        <li><strong>Residents organized first.</strong> Flagstaff's win came after nine months of one resident and then many showing up.</li>
        <li><strong>The contract was the pressure point.</strong> Every win happened at a council or board vote on the contract.</li>
        <li><strong>Public comment moved the room.</strong> Flagstaff had ninety minutes of public comment, almost all against Flock, before the vote flipped.</li>
        <li><strong>Local guardrails weren't enough.</strong> Flagstaff canceled even after the police added their own limits, because the network and the company were the problem, not the local officers.</li>
        <li><strong>They supported their police and still voted no.</strong> "No reflection on the department" was the repeated refrain. You can respect local officers and still pull the cameras.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <h2>Safford Can Be Next</h2>
    <p>
      None of these towns are bigger or richer or more political than Safford. They had the same cameras, the same company, the same network. What they had that we're building now: residents who showed up, receipts in hand, at the meeting where the contract was on the table.
    </p>

    <div class="cta-banner">
      <h3>Do What They Did</h3>
      <p>Sign the petition, file the records request, and show up at the next council or board meeting. That's the exact path these towns walked.</p>
      <a href={`${base}petition/`} class="btn">Sign the Petition</a>
      <a href={`${base}meetings/`} class="btn btn-outline">Meeting Schedule</a>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
